According to him, if there is a news story that they air; they put it in the context of Turkish history. “If it would not be on today’s TV, it would not be aired.” TV drama has always been at the forefront of society in their country; and over the years, Turkey has cemented a place for itself on the global stage, said Darwish. “It’s very popular there; Turkish runs are long-lasting, and sometimes it’s easier to sell TV series more than feature films.” Darwish says that it’s a trend that is catching on elsewhere. “This is a great thing in connecting and promoting society-to-society dialogue with the rest of the world.” Darwish sits on various IFTA committees, including Dedicated Programme Awards and New Talent Programme Awards. – elwood.shreve@indcatholicnews.com
